# Solving the `sorry` in the Lean 4 Proof

The error message `The given file contains a sorry on the last line, column 2.` indicates that the proof is incomplete. Specifically, the proof ends with a `sorry` tactic, which means the proof is not finished.

Looking at the proof context, the main goal is to prove:
```tactics
⊢ (do
      let a ← runToRound (Fin.last n) (lens.stmt.toFunA outerStmtIn) (lens.wit.toFunA (outerStmtIn, outerWitIn)) P
      Prod.mk a.1 <;> (lens.lift (outerStmtIn, outerWitIn) <;> P.output a.2).liftComp (oSpec + fun i => pSpec.Type ↑i)) =
    do
    let a ← runToRound (Fin.last n) (lens.stmt.toFunA outerStmtIn) (lens.wit.toFunA (outerStmtIn, outerWitIn)) P
    (fun a_1 => (a.1, lens.lift (outerStmtIn, outerWitIn) a_1)) <;> (P.output a.2).liftComp (oSpec + fun i => pSpec.Type ↑i)
```

This equality involves two `do` blocks. The left side is:
```tactics
let a := runToRound (Fin.last n) (lens.stmt.toFunA outerStmtIn) (lens.wit.toFunA (outerStmtIn, outerWitIn)) P
Prod.mk a.1 <;> (lens.lift (outerStmtIn, outerWitIn) <;> P.output a.2).liftComp (oSpec + fun i => pSpec.Type ↑i)
```

And the right side is:
```tactics
let a := runToRound (Fin.last n) (lens.stmt.toFunA outerStmtIn) (lens.wit.toFunA (outerStmtIn, outerWitIn)) P
(fun a_1 => (a.1, lens.lift (outerStmtIn, outerWitIn) a_1)) <;> (P.output a.2).liftComp (oSpec + fun i => pSpec.Type ↑i)
```

To prove this equality, we need to show that the expressions on both sides are definitionally equal or can be simplified to the same form. Let's analyze the structure.

The left side uses `Prod.mk a.1 <;> ...`. This is applying `Prod.mk` to `a.1` and then applying the rest of the expression to the result. `Prod.mk` takes two arguments, so `Prod.mk a.1` is a function expecting another argument.

The right side uses `(fun a_1 => (a.1, lens.lift (outerStmtIn, outerWitIn) a_1)) <;> ...`. This is a lambda function that takes `a_1` and returns a pair `(a.1, lens.lift ... a_1)`. This is then applied to the result of `P.output a.2`.

The key insight is that `a.1` (the first part of `a`) is being used in both cases. The structure of the expressions is similar, with the main difference being how the pair is constructed.

We can try to prove this using `simp` and `congr` tactics.

